Project.b05dc565-670f-40ea-832d-21f70008.title: AirBnB clone
Project.b05dc565-670f-40ea-832d-21f70008.description: This is an attempt to re-create the AirBnB website
Project.b05dc565-670f-40ea-832d-21f70008.readme:
The console is the first segment of the AirBnB project at Holberton School that will collectively cover fundamental concepts of higher level programming. The goal of AirBnB project is to eventually deploy our server a simple copy of the AirBnB Website(HBnB). A command interpreter is created in this segment to manage objects for the AirBnB(HBnB) website.

Functionalities of this command interpreter:
Create a new object (ex: a new User or a new Place)
Retrieve an object from a file, a database etc...
Do operations on objects (count, compute stats, etc...)
Update attributes of an object
Destroy an object

Project.4bf49282-7a02-4649-90e6-52a60642.title: Monty
Project.4bf49282-7a02-4649-90e6-52a60642.description: This is one of my ALX projects on Stacks and Queues
Project.4bf49282-7a02-4649-90e6-52a60642.readme:
MONTY
Tasks on stack and queue

THE MONTY LANGUAGE Monty 0.98 is a scripting language that is first compiled into Monty byte code (Just like python). It relies on a unique stack with specific instructions to manipulate it. The goal of this project is to create an interpreter for Monty bytecode files

Usage: Monty The Monty program runs the bytecode line by line and stops if either: It executed properly every line of the file, It finds an error on the file, An error occurs.

Project.9f513554-06f0-42b2-8137-84ab9c09.title: Simple Shell
Project.9f513554-06f0-42b2-8137-84ab9c09.description: This is an attempt to re-create the simple shell environment with C language
Project.9f513554-06f0-42b2-8137-84ab9c09.readme: This is a simple shell program modeled after the likes of early Unix shells such as the Thompson, Korn or C shells. It was written by Dennis Akinwonjowo and Anselm Chidera for a project via Holberton School. The shell provides an interface by which a user may interact with the kernel, as well as a number of built-in tools to ease this interaction. Running in interactive mode, the program solicits a command line from the user via the terminal, parses this input for valid commands, and executes them accordingly. Users may also pipe output from other commands into the shell, causing it to run in non-interactive mode. In this mode, the shell will not prompt the user for input and will automatically exit upon completion of the commands received. For further information regarding functionality and support, refer to the included man page.

Project.531dd777-53f0-4166-b5e2-402b268f.title: Printf
Project.531dd777-53f0-4166-b5e2-402b268f.description: This is an attempt to recreate the printf bash function
Project.531dd777-53f0-4166-b5e2-402b268f.readme:
_printf()
The printf is a project collaboration between Dennis and Chidera, students of ALX.

_printf() is a function that performs formatted output conversion and print data.

Prototype:

int _printf(const char *format, ...)
Format is the string being printed.

_printf() is a variadic function, it can receives n arguments that replace by n tags written inside the string.

The format tags prototype is the following:

%[flags][length]specifier
The return value is the amount of chars printed.
